<P>
<P>
<H2>Friday 20th December declared day of mourning</H2>
<P><I></I>
<P>
<P>Revolted by the cold-blooded murder of its delegates, the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) declared Friday 20th December 1996 a day of mourning and invited National Societies, the International Federation of  Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies and other humanitarian organizations, both governmental and non-governmental, to observe it in the way they felt most appropriate (reduced activity, flags at half-mast, special ceremonies, public statements).<BR>

<P>In Geneva, to pay tribute to the selfless dedication of the six persons murdered in the course of their humanitarian duties, and to express abhorrence at the vile act that put an end to their lives, a religious ceremony was held at St-Pierre Cathedral at 11 a.m., in the presence, amongst others, of friends of the victims, of ICRC staff, representatives of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, of embassies accredited to the United Nations in Geneva and of other humanitarian organisations.<BR>

<P><A HREF="45fe.htm">Homage to assassinated delegates pronounced by ICRC President Cornelio Sommaruga at Saint-Pierre Cathedral, Geneva</A>  20 Decembre 1996<BR>

<P><A HREF="461e.htm">Homage to assassinated ICRC delegates pronounced by Ms Marion Harroff-Tavel, Deputy Delegate General for Operations in Eastern Europe and Central Asia, at Saint-Pierre Cathedral, Geneva</A> 20 December 1996 <BR>

<P><A HREF="461a.htm">Memorial Ceremony for the ICRC delegates killed in Chechenia, address by Stephen Davey, Under-Secretary General, Communications and Policy Coordination, International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies</A> 20 Decembre 1996<BR>

<P>At noon, representatives of humanitarian organizations marched in silence from the Place des Nations, Geneva, to ICRC headquarters where they placed flowers before the International Committee of the Red Cross flag.<BR>

<P><center><BR>

