<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Message from the Director</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>Message from the Director</H1>
<HR>
<P>

<IMG SRC="diana.gif" align=top>
<P>Dr. Diana Freckman<P>

<H2>The Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory: Interdisciplinary Research in a
University Setting</H2>

Improving our understanding of the ecological complexity of the world we live
in increasingly requires us to ask questions that can only be answered by bringing
a wide range of skills to bear on them. Advances in our knowledge of ecological
relationships and our ability to put that knowledge to work to solve practical
problems will depend more and more upon research that integrates the perspectives
and techniques of several disciplines. The Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory
(NREL), an ecosystem research center that will celebrate its 30th anniversary in
1997, has a long tradition of bringing scientists from different disciplines
together to examine complicated ecological problems. Originally focused on the
grasslands of the western United States, research at NREL today spans the globe
and contributes to the scientific basis for understanding the interactions that
sustain our environment, locally, regionally and globally.<P>
A unique feature of the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory among ecosystem
  centers is its position as an interdisciplinary research institute in a
  university setting. Organized as a research unit within the College of Natural
  Resources at Colorado State University, NREL cuts across disciplinary and
  structural divisions. Some of its scientists are affiliated entirely with NREL.
  Others have joint appointments with university departments, and some are
  employees of federal or state agencies. They come together in an environment
  that minimizes disciplinary boundaries and enhances creative thought.
  Researchers and students at NREL include organism ecologists, biogeochemists,
  computer scientists, modelers and atmospheric scientists who work together to
  address complex local, national and global problems. The laboratory's new
  facility in the recently completed Natural and Environmental Sciences Building
  features state-of-the-art computer facilities, geographic information systems
  (GIS) and the newest technology for chemical and physical analysis to support
  these collaborations.<P>

<IMG SRC="directors.gif"><BR>
<I>From left, Judson M. Harper, Vice President for Research, Colorado State
University; A. Allen Dyer, Dean, College of Natural Resources; Diana W. Freckman,
Director, NREL; Edward T. Elliott, Associate Director, NREL. Photo by William
Cotton</I>
<P>

The Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory contributes to Colorado State University's
  mission of teaching, research and service. Our scientists play key roles in
  academic departments by teaching and serving as mentors for future scientists.
  The broad range of laboratory and field experiences that they provide for
  students contributes to the training of a new generation of scientists committed
  to working in an interdisciplinary fashion to solve environmental problems.
  Through their work in our community schools as well as through the involvement
  of high school students, undergraduates and volunteers in the daily activities
  of the laboratory, NREL staff members share their excitement about science and
  ecosystems with students of all ages and contribute to a scientifically
  knowledgeable public.<P>
Current research at the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory focuses on five
  themes: the long-term response of ecosystems to global change, the functioning
  of agricultural ecosystems, linkages between the atmosphre and terrestrial
  ecosystems, the interactions of plants and animals, the role of humans in
  ecosystems, and the synthesis and modeling of knowledge gained from ecosystem
  studies. Each of the essays to follow illustrates not only the strengths of an
  interdisciplinary approach to dealing with complex questions, but also the
  importance of basic research in the search for solutions to the environmental
  problems that face Colorado, the nation and the world. Programs will continue
  to emerge at NREL as research shows the need for incorporating new disciplines
  and technologies and as synthesis of research results and scholarship generates
  new perspectives on environmental problems. These essays, written in the spirit
  of scientific collaboration by those who are involved in the programs, stress
 the achievements of interdisciplinary research at the Natural Resource Ecology
Laboratory.<P>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="../NREL/nrel_info.html">Back to the Index</A><P>
