<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Introduction to the NREL</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<A NAME="introduction"><H2>Introduction to the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory</H2></A>
The Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL), a part of Colorado State
University in Fort Collins, Colorado, is dedicated to the study of ecological
systems and to the application of scientific knowledge to the preservation and
management of natural resources. NREL is an interdisciplinary research center
within the university's College of Natural Resources. The 35 scientists who
comprise the laboratory's senior staff represent a range of disciplines in the
biological, physical and social sciences; our collaborative research focuses on
ecosystems. Research programs are funded primarily by grants and contracts from
federal and state agencies with additional support from private corporations.<P>
Situated at the edge of the foothills that mark the boundary between the Rocky
  Mountains and the rangelands and croplands of the Great Plains, NREL was
  established in 1967 to administer the multidisciplinary Grassland Biome Study
  of the International Biological Program (IBP). Over the years since that study
  was completed, the scope of research at NREL has expanded to include projects
  on every continent and topics ranging from the soil microbial dynamics
  associated with the grazing of bison to global-scale studies of climate change
  and its impact on the terrestrial carbon cycle. Despite the diversity of study
  sites, scales and topics, the ecosystems approach to research questions runs as
  a common thread throughout our work.<P>
Ecologists traditionally studied individual organisms and their interactions with
  each other and with their environment. Early ecosystems studies focused instead
  on the flux of energy and materials among components of systems rather than on
  the components themselves. Research at NREL has improved our ability to
  penetrate the complexities of ecosystems by linking the dynamics of elements
  such as carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus in the biota, the soils and ultimately
  the atmosphere. George Van Dyne, first director of NREL, recognized the
  importance of bringing together researchers with diverse knowledge to work in
  interdisciplinary teams in order to address the ecosystem-level problems facing
  managers of natural resources. Clear understanding of the complex interactions
  that characterize whole ecosystems is required if we are to devise management
  strategies for the conservation and use of natural resources that will assure
  the long-term viability of the biosphere.<P>
Systems-level studies of these complx interactions require a wide range of
  knowledge, skills and tools. NREL scientists have been pioneers in the
  development and use of mathematical models that aid researchers in assimilating,
  organizing and understanding the large amounts of data and information needed
  to describe complex biological systems. Such models not only assist in the
  organization of research but also provide a means of testing our understanding
  of the structure and functioning of ecosystems. Ecosystem-level models have
  become important tools for managers charged with making decisions about natural
  resources. Models that were developed at NREL, such as Century, are widely used
  to test the implications of various management and climate-change scenarios.<P>
Several basic themes that are common to the research efforts undertaken at NREL
  are critical to the development of ecological theory. Some of the initial
  impetus to pursue these themes comes from the unanswered questions arising from
  the IBP research. But the pursuit has been spurred as well by the practical
  quest for a better understanding of how human activities modify the environment
  and for ways of resolving the conflict between sustaining the biosphere and
  addressing human needs.<p>
These themes include the long-term response of ecosystems to change, linkages
  between terrestrial ecosystems and the atmosphere, interactions between plants
  and animals, the structure and functioning of agricultural ecosystems, and the
  human contribution to ecosystem dynamics. The essays that follow describe
  various NREL studies that reflect these themes. These essays articulate some of
  the fundamental characteristics of our research philosophy. Critical linkages
  across sub-disciplinary boundaries provide the starting point of our research
  endeavors. Scientists at NREL are engaged in defining and understanding the
  connections between the processes that are important at one level of biological
  organization, such as the individual organism, and those that are important at
  other levels, such as populations, communities or whole ecological systems.<P>
We are now applying the ecosystem approach to new challenges. They include:<P>
<P>
<UL>
  <LI>Incorporating human activity into the study of ecosystems;
  <LI>Determining the role of biodiversity and biotic conservation in ecosystem
dynamics at various scales;
  <LI>Assessing potential risks to the sustainability of ecosystems;
  <LI>Studying the effects of global change on ecosystems and the ways in which
ecosystems modify these changes.
</UL>
<P>
Our scientific activities and findings over the years speak to our commitment to
developing a better understanding of the ecosystems that support us and a greater
appreciation of the earth that we inhabit.<P>
<P>
<B>Organization and Activities<P>
</B>Although it has many ties to departments of the College of Natural Resources
at Colorado State University, NREL is organized as a research unit rather than as
an academic department. Staff members are housed primarily in a single facility
equipped with laboratories and computer facilities where specialists are available
to assist the research efforts. NREL scientists train graduate students and
postdoctoral investigators, and many staff members have teaching appointments in
university departments. In 1992 and again in 1995, the university designated NREL
as a Program of Research and Scholarly Excellence, recognizing its local, national
and international contributions to ecosystem research and education.<P>
<P>
This ability to reach across academic disciplines has enabled the laboratory to
extend its efforts to conduct research in collaboration with numerous state and
federal agencies, both nationally and internationally. In cooperation with the
U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) Agricultural Research Service and the
university's departments of Forest Science and Rangeland Ecosystem Science, NREL
participates in a field research site in the Central Plains Experimental Range
(CPER). This site became part of the National Science Foundation's Long-Term
Ecological Research (LTER) program in 1982. NREL scientists conduct a wide variety
of studies at this site that focus on such topics as plant-animal interactions,
soil biotic processes, nutrient cycling, greenhouse gas emissions, the formation
of soils and the response of grasslands productivity to climate variation and
land-use changes.<P>
Research at NREL on grassland and agricultural ecosystems has expanded from the
  original focus on the semiarid shortgrass steppe of the Great Plains to include
  networks representing the entire central United States and as well as studies
  in regions of Mongolia, China and East Africa. NREL scientists also carry out
  research projects in the alpine and subalpine ecosystems of the Rocky Mountains,
  in the arctic and sub-arctic ecosystems of Alaska, Canada and northern Europe
  and in the dry valleys of Antarctica as well as several tropical countries.<p>
NREL researchers have assumed an ever-increasing role in the application of
  scientific knowledge to the formulation of environmental policy and the solution
  of management problems. Collaborative projects have been established with a
  number of agencies within the U.S. Department of Agriculture, Department of
  Interior and Environmental Protection Agency as well as the Colorado Division
  of Wildlife. Research efforts at home and abroad provide educational
  opportunities for students and environmental solutions for natural resource
  managers as well as addressing basic scientific questions.<P>
Scientists at the NREL also participate in the work of national and international
  committees, such as the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, that are
  addressing the effects of climate change, acid deposition, elevated carbon
  dioxide levels, land degradation, deforestation, ultraviolet radiation and the
  loss of biodiversity. Staff members have been invited to brief government
  officials, legislators and resource managers on a variety of environmental
  issues.<P>
NREL staff members are regularly asked to serve on a wide variety of governmental
  and non-governmental committees, including boards and panels of the National
  Science Foundation, the Department of Agriculture, the Department of Energy, the
  Department of the Interior, the Environmental Protection Agency, the National
  Aeronautics and Space Administration, the National Research Council and the
  National Academy of Sciences. One senior scientist has recently completed a term
  as president of the American Institute of Biological Sciences and a member of
  the board of the Association of Ecosystem Research Centers; another served as
  director of the Sustainable Biosphere Program. Several NREL scientists ar
  members of committees and working groups of the Global Change and Terrestrial
  Ecosystems study, a core project of the International Geosphere-Biosphere
  Programme. Many staff members serve on committees of the Ecological Society of
  America.<P>
<P>

<IMG SRC="grad.gif"><BR>
<I>NREL graduate students Virginia Valentine, Maurya Falkner, Susan Smith, Richard
Alward and Menwyelet Atsedu. Photo by William Cotton</I>
<P>
<HR>
