<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Long-Term Observations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<A NAME="long-term"><H2>Long-Term Observations Yield Insight Into Ecosystem Responses To Climate Change</H2> </A>
Natural systems have rhythms and progressions over time that strongly
influence, if not dictate, the characteristics of individual components. Variation
in climate, periodic disturbances and internal community dynamics are all involved
in shaping ecosystems. Long-term observations are required in order to formulate
meaningful, testable hypotheses that describe and predict ecosystem responses to
changing conditions.<P>
Many research projects of the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL) depend
  upon long-term observations. Studies begun in 1968 as part of the Grassland
  Biome Study continue today under the Shortgrass Steppe Long-Term Ecological
  Research (LTER) Program. Other long-term research efforts at NREL include the
  Loch Vale Watershed Long-Term Research and Monitoring Program (LVWS) and the
  National Atmospheric Deposition Program (NADP), which monitors atmospheric
  deposition throughout the United States.<P>
<P>
<B>Shortgrass Steppe Long-Term Ecological Research<P>
</B>An example from the LTER program shows us how the time span of observations
can affect conclusions about the impact of climate variation on ecosystems. Four
years of data from the 1970s, collected during the Grassland Biome Study, suggest
that the annual net production of plants at the LTER site averages about 90 grams
per square meter (g/m2) but that large decreases can be expected as a result of
fluctuations in weather (Figure 1a). Twenty-one years of data from the Grassland
Biome Study and the LTER program lead to the same conclusion about average
production but different conclusions about the response to weather extremes
 (Figure 1b). If we extend the record back to 1939 using U.S. Forest Service and
Agricultural Research Service observations, however, long-term average production
over the 54-year period is 100 g/m<em sup>2</em>, and fluctuations can be as much as
60% in either direction (Figure 1c). Our understanding of ecosystem behavior is
thus linked to the length of record available for interpretation.
The goal of the Shortgrass Steppe LTER program since its beginning has been to
  understand the long-term processes that account for the origin and sstainability
  of shortgrass ecosystems. Three topics addressed by LTER researchers illustrate
  the relationship between this goal and specific research projects.<P>
<P>
<B>Development of Landscapes and Soils During the Holocene<P>
</B>The evolutionary history of the shortgrass steppe or grassland is preserved
in Holocene paleosols, buried soils formed in ancient landscapes that retain an
imprint of the climate and ecosystems prevailing during their formation. Gene
Kelly and Caroline Yonker of Colorado State University's Department of Soil and
Crop Science use the stable carbon isotopic composition of paleosol organic
matter, soil carbonate and opal phytoliths (silica deposits from grass leaves) to
characterize the vegetation of the era and make inferences about Holocene climate
change.<P>
Isotopic characterization of paleosol constituents led to the identification of
  three soil-forming intervals during the last 10,000 years. Cool-season C<em
  sub>3</em> grasses appear to have been the dominant vegetation in the early
  Holocene, during a period of cooler climates. They gave way during mid- and late
  Holocene soil-forming intervals to dominance by C<em sub>4</em> grasses, which
  process carbon dioxide more efficiently. Understanding paleosol formation, in
  the context of the geologic episodes that resulted in their burial, allows
  interpretation of the magnitude of ecological and landscape responses to climate
  variability.<P>
<P>
<B>Response of Dominant Plant Species to Disturbances<P>
<I></B>Bouteloua gracilis</I>, or blue grama grass, accounts for 70% to 90% of the
productivity of shortgrass ecosystems. Of all the grass species in the ecosystem,
it is most able to resist grazing and drought. As a consequence, blue grama is a
key species to consider in making management decisions, whether for conservation
or for sustainable livestock production. The prevailing view about blue grama at
the start of the LTER project was that this grass was a relict species,
established under climactic conditions that no longer existed. Researchers thought
that blue grama would never regrow once an area was disturbed. Over the past 13
years, field and modeling studies led by NREL scientists William Lauenroth, Debra
Coffin and Ingrid Burke have shown conclusively that blue grama does recover,
although slowly, after disturbance. Studies in abandoned fields have demonstrated
that the degree of recovery varies greatly from field to field, but that blue
grama has recovered to some degree in all of them. Because of the critical role
that blue grama plays in the sustainability of shortgrass ecosystems, these
results have important consequences for management of disturbed areas.<P>

<IMG SRC="pawnee.gif"><BR>
<I>NREL researchers and a volunteer from the Earthwatch program collect soil and
plant samples in an abandoned field. Photo by W.K. Lauenroth</I>

<P>
<B>Responses of the Ecosystem to Grazing<P>
</B>Large herbivores have been an important component of shortgrass ecosystems
 since the retreat of the Pleistocene glaciers and the start of the Holocene about
10,000 years ago. Cattle currently graze about 45% of the shortgrass steppe area,
and grazing will continue to be important because much of the land is marginal for
sustainable crop production. Long-term research conducted by Daniel Milchunas and
Lauenroth has established that grazing has a small effect on the plant species
composition and net primary productivity of the ecosystem. Invasions by exotic and
native weed species are more likely to occur, in fact, in ungrazed plots than in
 grazed ones. Burke has also established that soil organic matter pools and
nutrient availability are affected only slightly by grazing.<P>
We conclude from these results that shortgrass ecosystems are highly resistant to
  grazing. The plant species in the shortgrass steppe evolved under strong
  pressure from large herbivores and periodic drought. These forces favor plant
  species that have morphological and physiological adaptations to drought and
  grazing. They also result in ecosystems with more than 90% of their total
  organic matter in the soil.<P>
<IMG SRC="daniel.gif"><BR>
<I>Robin Smith and Daniel Milchunas inject compounds enriched with 15N as a tracer
into the soil profile to assess competition for nutrients between shrubs and
grasses. Photo by M. Lindquist
 </I>
<P>
<B>Loch Vale Watershed Research and Monitoring<P>
</B>Although the alpine and subalpine environment of the Loch Vale Watershed
(LVWS), located in Rocky Mountain National Park in the Front Range of the Colorado
Rockies, differs greatly from the shortgrass steppe, our approach to understanding
the structure and functioning of these ecosystems is similar. From its beginning
in 1980, LVWS research led by NREL scientist Jill Baron has addressed the problem
of differentiating the consequences of disturbance caused by human activity from
natural variation. One major focus is on understanding ecosystem responses to the
deposition of substances from the atmosphere.<P>
Research at Loch Vale began with paleohistorical studies designed to project the
  record of atmospheric deposition back to preindustrial times. Lake sediments
  preserve a record of substances that enter the atmosphere through industrial
  emissions and are deposited over the landscape. Metals and algal indicators of
  deposition found in these sediments provide the baseline for interpreting the
  results of long-term observations of precipitation and the chemical composition
  of surface waters. Interpretation of the sediment records has allowed us to
  conclude that the deposition of sulfate in rain and snow does not currently pose
  an ecological threat, but that the deposition of nitrate and ammonium may, in
  fact, be excessive for the maintenance of existing plant communities.<P>
We use deposition chemistry data, collected from the LVWS National Atmospheric
  Deposition Program site, in conjunction with data on the chemical composition
  of alpine and subalpine streams to construct an overall picture of the flux of
  major nutrients and pollutants into and out of the basin. These measurements are
  supplemented with in-depth studies of ecosystem processes. Examples include
  studies of hydrologic flows, including snow redistribution and melting patterns,
  nutrient cycling in wetlands and in old-growth forests dominated by Englemann
  spruce and subalpine fir, and the sources and fate of nitrogen and carbon in
  tundra, forests and lakes.<P>
Models are used in LVWS studies both to test hypotheses and to generate them. For
  example, Baron, Dennis Ojima and William Parton of the NREL and Elsabeth Holland
  of the National Center for Atmospheric Research used an application of the
  NREL's Century model to explore the possibility that high concentrations of
  nitrogen in lakes and streams in the watershed are the result of nitrogen
  saturation in alpine tundra and subalpine forest ecosystems. Current levels of
  nitrate and ammonium deposition from the atmosphere are many times greater than
  those of pre-industrial times, potentially providing terrestrial ecosystems with
  more nitrogen than plants and microbes can use. Simulation results suggest that
  nitrogen availability currently limits productivity in forests and that
  saturation has not occurred. But they also suggest that nitrogen no longer
  limits growth in the alpine tundra, and that nitrogen leached from this
  terrestrial source may be sufficient to account for the levels observed in
  streams (Figure 2). In conjunction with the Niwot Ridge LTER and U.S. Geological
  Survey Water, Energy and Biogeochemical Budgets projects, we are conducting a
  series of field experiments to test these model results and to confirm or refute
  the proposition that nitrogen saturation is an ongoing phenomenon in the Front
 Range.
<P>
<B>National Atmospheric Deposition Program<P>
</B>Both the LTER and LVWS studies rely on monitoring results from the National
Atmospheric Deposition Program (NADP), an NREL program developed and led by James
Gibson. Organized in 1978, the NADP assumed responsibility for the federal
National Trends Network (NTN) in 1982. The combined program now has 200 sites
throughout the U.S. In order to assure the quality of the data, NREL staff member
David Bigelow established a quality assurance program for the NADP/NTN. Over the
years, the NADP has built a comprehensive, high-quality record of the geographical
patterns and temporal trends of chemical deposition in precipitation that is the
most comprehensive in the world.<P>
Originally organized in response to national concerns about the effects of acid
  precipitation, the program has provided policymakers with information not only
  on the geographical patterns and trends in acidic deposition, but also on the
  deposition of chemical nutrients. Framers of the 1990 revisions of the federal
  Clean Air Act made use of the NADP/NTN data set as they developed the new
  regulations. They will rely on these data in the future as they assess the
  effectiveness of the reduction in sulfur and nitrogen compounds called for in
  the 1990 amendments.<P>
<P>
<B>New Long-Term Research Programs</B><P>

Several new programs are increasing the scope of long-term research at NREL.
Gibson is developing a national program for the long-term measurement of
ultraviolet-B radiation to assess its potential effects on crops and forests.<P>

<IMG SRC="jeff.gif"><BR>
<I>Jeffrey Welker installs soil respiration collars for studies of carbon dioxide
exchange at Niwot Ridge, Colorado. Photo by A.N. Parsons</I><P>

Jeffrey Welker, postdoctoral student Andrew Parsons and colleagues from the
  University of Colorado have begun a five-year study of the effects of changes
  in snow cover and summer temperatures on the structure and function of arctic
  ecosystems in Alaska. This project is part of the International Tundra
  Experiment (ITEX), which comprises a network of olar and alpine sites where
  similar studies are underway. Researchers are using both modeling simulations
  and natural gradients in snow cover to predict long-term consequences of changes
  in carbon and nitrogen dynamics in arctic ecosystems.<P>


<IMG SRC="mcmurdo.gif"><BR>
<I>Diana Freckman and Ericha Courtright of NREL and Mengchi Ho of Dartmouth College
collect nematode samples in Antarctic Dry Valleys. Photo by J.T. Freckman </I><P>

As a participant in the McMurdo Dry Valley LTER and in projects with colleagues
  from Dartmouth College, Diana Freckman is studying soil nematodes in desert
  conditions in the Antarctic. She is examining the role of these dominant
  invertebrates in key ecosystem processes and in the response of soils to
  disturbance.<P>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="../NREL/nrel_info.html">Back to the Index</A><P>
