</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Agroecosystems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<A NAME="agroecosystems"><H2>Agroecosystems: From Process Studies to Regional Assessments</H2></A>
Human beings practice agriculture, the cultivation of the soil to produce food
and fiber, over a significant portion of the land area of the earth. Agriculture
thus affects natural processes at every spatial scale, from local to global. In
the late 1970's, Vernon Cole and his coworkers at the Natural Resource Ecology
Laboratory (NREL) developed one of the first programs for studying agricultural
ecosystems (agroecosystems) to be funded by the National Science Foundation. Since
then, NREL scientists have focused on gaining a fundamental understanding of the
biogeochemical flows related to the dynamics of soil organic matter (SOM) and the
cycling of carbon, nitrogen, sulfur and phosphorus. Studies of SOM in
agroecosystems and simulation analyses with the NREL's Century model have provided
a broad base of knowledge that is applicable to the dynamics of nutrients within
ecosystems in general. We are using this understanding to address ecosystem
questions at multiple scales of resolution in time and space.<p>
The approach that many NREL researchers use for dynamic regional ecosystem
  analysis is illustrated in a diagram developed by Edward Elliott and Cole in
  1989 (Figure 1). It makes use of models that depend upon knowledge derived from
  experimental studies and field observations of agroecosystem processes. These
  models are subsequently used to make large-scale and long-term projections of
  the ways in which changes in climate and management practices can influence
  ecosystem properties such as SOM content and primary production.<P>
Extrapolating from small-scale studies to assessments at the regional scale
  requires spatially explicit information on the variables, such as temperature,
  precipitation, soil texture and historical management practices, that regulate
  ecosystem processes. This information is organized into databases using
  geographic information system (GIS) programs. These databases provide input on
  these critical variables with which to run models for different locations across
  the landscape or region. Results from model simulations are then projected back
  onto the region from which the data were obtained.<P>
We evaluate model analyses by comparing simulations with data obtained from a
  network of sites covering the region over which projections are being made.
  Well-tested models used in conjunction with the appropriate
  geographically-organized databases are our best tools for investigating the ways
  in which land use, crop productivity and trace gas fluxes may be influenced by
  future changes in climate and management practices.<P>
Key to the success of our approach is the teamwork of researchers who study
  ecosystem processes, sample site networks, organize geographical databases and
  carry out modeling simulations. For example, NREL researchers including Elliott,
  William Hunt, John Moore, and other colleagues, established the importance of
  interactions among components of the underground foodwebs in accelerating the
  cycling of elements essential for plant growth. These scientists were the first
  to dmonstrate that soil fauna enhance the growth of plants and that soil
  structure controls trophic interactions (Figure 2) and their subsequent
  influence on nutrient dynamics. The concept of functional groups of soil biota
  that contribute to soil biogeochemistry was incorporated in model simulations,
  which predicted a significant role for soil fauna in soil fertility. Diana
  Freckman, Robert Niles, and their coworkers continue this soil ecology research
  in collaboration with other colleagues at Colorado State University.<P>

<IMG SRC="microb.gif"><BR>
<I>Figure 2: Microbial life in the soil is constrained by the soil structure, which
affects the ability of the organisms to move and feed. This figure depicts foodweb
interactions among key players in one square centimeter of grassland soil. Figure
by S.L. Rose
</I><P>

The Century model, developed by William Parton, Cole and their coworkers at NREL,
  incorporates the concept of organic matter fractions with differing turnover
  times. Elliott and his students and colleagues have isolated fractions with
  laboratory techniques to separate the soil physically into its components. This
  approach is based on the premise that the structure of the soil, as expressed
  in the aggregation of soil particles and organic matter, is a primary factor
  controlling the accessibility of organic matter for soil organisms, its
  subsequent mineralization and the availability of nutrients in soil.<P>
Isolation of one of these physical fractions, particulate organic matter (POM),
  has stimulated a series of studies across the U.S. and around the world to
  examine this fraction as a major contributor to the long-term fertility of
  soils. POM seems to account for a greater proportion of total SOM dynamics than
  any previously isolated fraction. We are currently evaluating these methods on
  soils obtained around the world.<P>
In another project, Cole and other scientists at NREL are collaborating with Gary
  Peterson and Dwayne Westfall of the Colorado State University Soil and Crop
  Sciences Department in establishing long-term field experiments at three sites
  in eastern Colorado. These studies are designed to determine the feasibility of
  increased cropping frequency with reductions in bare fallow, ground that is kept
  bare during the growing season to trap water in the soil profile for the next
 growing season. Now in their twelfth year, these studies are showing that the new
cropping systems are economically superior and improve soil properties.<P>

<IMG SRC="plow.gif"><BR>
<I>Change in land use affects regional biodiversity and water and radiation budgets,
resulting in changes in soil productivity and trace gas emissions.
</I><P>

The Great Plains of the western U.S. provide a wonderful field laboratory for
  studies of the regional distribution of SOM. The region is a climatic
  checkerboard; temperature varies north to south, and precipitation, from east
  to west. Cole, Ingrid Burke and other investigators from NREL observed that the
  organic matter patterns found within the region, obtained through analysis of
  large databases of soil samples, were primarily accounted for by precipitation,
  temperature and soil texture. The researchers derived projections of SOM loss
  across the Great Plains for different soil textures by using regional climatic
  data as input for the Century model and comparing the output to existing data.
  They were able to obtain accurate predictions of SOM levels using only a few
  variables: climate, soil texture and the lignin content of plants.<P>
Burke also used geographically organized climate and soil texture data to derive
  SOM and plant productivity maps, first for northeastern Colorado and eventually
  for the central grassland region. Some results are shown in the first part of
  a figure that accompanies the article on atmosphere-ecosystem interactions in
  this report. The northeastern Colorado study showed that, while plant production
  was primarily controlled by precipitation, the texture of the soil was the
  predominant control over SOM. Results indicated that agricultural management
  practices over the last 50 years were likely to have had a far greater impact
  on SOM stores in the central grassland region than potential climate changes
  over a similar period. A modeling simulation conducted by Cole and Keith
  Paustian predicted, in fact, that the increasing trend of crop yields and
  adoption of no-till methods would render the Great Plains and the Corn Belt a
  significant sink for carbon from the atmosphere.<P>
NREL scientists are currently making regional assessments of the changes in soil
  carbon that may take place with alternative management scenarios for lands
  currently under the U.S. Conservaion Reserve Program (CRP), which subsidizes
  farmers for fields planted in grass. These analyses have contributed to the
  federal decision-making process. Such model predictions must be corroborated,
  however, if they are to be useful to policymakers.<P>
Regional databases are essential if we are to have confidence in projections made
  with models. Elliott and Paustian have brought together a network of sites and
  a group of collaborators in one of the largest long-term ecological experiments
  ever conducted on disturbance and biogeochemistry. The project includes more
  than 40 agricultural experimental sites, established by the U.S. Department of
  Agriculture's Agricultural Research Service and the Land Grant universities.
  These sites are located throughout the Great Plains and the Corn Belt.
  Preliminary analyses suggest that sequestration of soil carbon is enhanced when
  the flux of carbon into the soil is increased, and when soil disturbance is
  reduced. This effect appears to be greater in areas where precipitation is
  higher.<P>
Another important NREL network of sites developed by Burke and Debra Coffin
  consists of abandoned fields, reestablished as grasslands over periods of up to
  50 years, and their cultivated counterparts. Soil organic matter has increased
  significantly at many of these locations; the rate of increase is related to the
  texture of the soil and the climatic regime. These sites are being used to
  estimate the potential long-term impact of the CRP on SOM levels. Existing
  conservation reserve lands are currently being sampled as well.<P>

<IMG SRC="martin.gif"><BR>
<I>Martin Fowler conducts a greenhouse study of cores taken from wheat fields. Photo
by H.W. Hunt </I><P>

The agroecosystem science program at NREL has not only developed information
  useful for understanding agricultural ecosystems, it has also contributed to our
  fundamental knowledge of ecosystem biogeochemistry and organic matter dynamics.
  This knowledge contributes to our understanding of the impact of changes in both
 climate and management practices on agroecosystems over large areas and long time
periods, and it provides policymakers and managers with a scientifically sound
basis for making decisions.<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="../NREL/nrel_info.html">Back to the Index</A><P>
<A HREF="atmosphere.html">Next Section</A><P>

