<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure: Ecology and Atmospheric Science</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<A NAME="atmosphere"><H2>Ecology and Atmospheric Science: Studying the Interactions Between Ecosystems and the Atmosphere</H2></A>
Improvements in our understanding of ecological processes have played a major
role in the unraveling of important problems in the atmospheric sciences and
geophysics over the last decade. Earth scientists have observed increases in the
atmospheric concentrations of a number of biogenic trace gases during this period;
their observations have had, in turn, a massive impact on the practice of ecology.
Scientists at the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL), in collaboration
with colleagues at other laboratories, have become progressively more involved in
studying the interactions between ecosystems and the atmosphere as understanding
the effects of climate change has become a national and international priority.<P>
Ecologists have traditionally focused on understanding processes within
  ecosystems. They have attempted, in general, to identify scales of biological
  organization where external influences can be assumed to be weak relative to the
  effects of internal dynamics. Studies of ecosystem-atmosphere interactions, in
  contrast, focus on the relationship between atmospheric and ecological processes
  and on processes external to the ecosystem. These interactions can occur through
  the exchange of substances that have an influence on both ecosystems and the
  atmosphere. An example is water, which is exchanged through precipitation,
  evaporation and transpiration from plants. Because the spatial and temporal
  dynamics of precipitation have a profound influence on vegetation and soils,
  modeling the effects of precipitation on terrestrial ecosystems and on the
  exchange of water and energy between ecosystems and the atmosphere has become
  a major focus at NREL.<P>
Evaporation and transpiration, referred to collectively as evapotranspiration,
  have a reciprocal effect on atmospheric processes. The role of vegetation,
  topography and soils in regulating evapotranspiration and thus atmospheric
  processes has also been a major focus of modeling efforts among NREL scientists
  Jill Baron, Timothy Kittel, William Parton and David Schimel and collaborators
  such as Roger Pielke of the Atmospheric Sciences Department at Colorado State
  University and Steven Running of the University of Montana. Schimel, Parton,
  Kittel, Dennis Ojima, David Valentine and Ingrid Burke have also participated
  in large field programs that focused on transpiration. Among them was a study
  in the tallgrass prairie of Kansas that was supported by the National Aeronautic
  and Space Administration (NASA) as part of the International Satellite Land
  Surface Climatology Program. Ongoing projects have extended the range of
  questions asked about the exchange of water between ecosystems and the
  atmosphere. The South Platte Project, for example, focuses on the way topography
  and river systems redistribute water and thus alter the exchange with the
  atmosphere.<P>
Trace gases such as nitrous oxide (N<em sub>2</em>O), nitric oxide (NO), methane
  (CH<em sub>4</em>) and ammonia (NH<em sub>3</em>) are produced as by-products of the
  biogeochemical processes of decomposition and itrogen cycling. We can generally
  study the flux of elements in ecosystem-level processes such as primary
  production or carbon storage without needing to identify the gaseous emissions
  of nitrogen or carbon as discrete chemical compounds. The atmosphere, on the
  other hand, is affected by specific compounds in different ways. For example,
  N<em sub>2</em>O is a chemically inert but potent greenhouse gas. NO is one of the
  most potent reactive species of nitrogen controlling or regulating tropospheric
  ozone, itself a greenhouse gas. Former NREL student Elisabeth Holland and her
  coworkers at the National Center for
 Atmospheric Research (NCAR) in Boulder have found that NH3, while not directly
involved in the greenhouse effect, has a major effect on the pH of rain and may
influence global ecosystem carbon storage.<P>

<IMG SRC="field.gif"><BR>
<I>NREL researchers collect samples of native grasses for growth-chamber experiments
with elevated carbon dioxide. </I><P>

Collaborative studies by Parton, Valentine, Schimel, Ojima and research associate
  William Pulliam of the NREL and Arvin Mosier of the U.S. Department of
  Agriculture have progressed from measurements of the exchange of trace gases
  between ecosystems and the atmosphere and studies of the controls on rates of
  production to modeling trace-gas exchanges on a regional scale. This group has
  recently developed models that predict the fluxes of nitrogen trace gases and
  the ratios of the various chemical species based on biophysical constraints on
  the microbial ecology of the nitrogen cycle. While the modeling of gas fluxes
  is an important part of developing nitrogen budgets, a traditional concern in
  ecology, modeling the ratios of chemical species is motivated by questions that
  arise in atmospheric chemistry.<P>

<IMG SRC="cloud.gif><BR>
<I>Terrestrial ecosystems exchange water and trace gases with the atmosphere. Photo
by D.P. Coffin</I><P>

The study of atmosphere-ecosystem interactions has also stimulated a shift in the
  spatial scale of ecosystem field studies and modeling efforts. Environmental
  perturbations that modify the photochemistry of the atmosphere or the balance
  of energy can affect the atmosphere over areas ranging from tens to thousands
  of kilometers. The effects of long-lived, globally-distributed greenhouse gases
  such as carbon dioxide (CO<em sub>2</em>) or CH<em sub>4</em> can only be described in
  terms of global budgets because their effects on climate stem from changes in
  global concentrations. In the late 1970s, Mosier, Schimel, Parton, Robert
  Woodmansee and Vernon Cole, together with students from Colorado State's
  Agronomy Department, began to work on techniques for extrapolating ecological
  information to larger spatial scales, beginning with constructing organic matter
  budgets, studying trace-gas exchanges and using landscapes as building blocks
  for regional analyses.
In the mid 1980s, the NREL began using geographic information systems (GIS) and
  remote-sensing data to carry out spatial extrapolations and modeling. Schimel
  and Burke and their coworkers carried out studies in the Great Plains of the
  U.S., and Michael Coughenour, Jim Ellis and former NREL graduate student Robin
  Patten worked in the Turkana region of Kenya. Both GIS and remote-sensing
  technologies are now used for projects ranging from Burke's research on the
  impact of land use in the central grasslands of the U.S. to Ojima's modeling
  studies of the effects of climate change on grasslands around the globe. NREL
  has participated in efforts leading to basic improvements in GIS technology
  through a collaboration with IBM's Federal Systems Company and in research on
  the uses of remote sensing, carried out by Schimel and colleagues from NASA and
  the University of Colorado.<P>

<IMG SRC="regional.gif><BR>
<IMG SRC="us.gif><BR>
<IMG SRC="world.gif><BR>
<I>Figure 1: Soil carbon estimated at three scales with the NREL ecosystem model
Century. Within the grassland biome of the central United States (a), agricultural
land uses (1) were a major contributor to spatial distribution in soil carbon (2)
change over a 50 year period. 
The simulation of soil carbon for the entire U.S. (b) is based on a 0.5  x 0.5 
grid using average climate and soil properties from a U.S. Department of
Agriculture soils database. This simulation estimates carbon for potential natural
vegetation. At this scale, ecosystem type is an important determinant of carbon
storage.
In a simulation of global carbon storage (c), the model was run at representative
sites worldwide. The results were interpolated using a standard global climate
database and a United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization soils map for
physical properties. At this scale, climate and physical properties are the
primary determinants of carbon storage, and ecosystem type and the chemistry of
leaf litter are secondary determinants.
</I><P>

NREL scientists have developed versions of the laboratory's Century model with
  different levels of resolution, which have been used to study specific regions,
  the biomes of the whole U.S. and the entire globe (Figure 1 a-c). We simulated
  the effects of temperature on carbon storage at each of these scales in a
  variety of ways. A number of field studies and measurement programs are
  collecting data on larger scales as well. These projects include regional
  sampling networks for ecosystem properties ranging from soil organic matter to
  ultraviolet radiation and micro-meteorological flux measurements to
  remote-sensing measurements on a global scale.<P>
 NREL ecologists find themselves conducting research to answer questions raised
  by atospheric chemists, and colleagues in the atmospheric sciences find
  themselves learning ecology. If we view the atmosphere and the biosphere as
  linked through a complex set of feedbacks, in which the biota controls much of
  the chemistry of the atmosphere and atmospheric composition influences the biota
  through climate, solar radiation, ozone levels and nutrient transport and
 deposition, the ecological significance of atmosphere-ecosystem studies becomes
clear. Such studies are inherently interdisciplinary. The interaction among
researchers from different disciplines has provoked debate over priorities, but
it has also expanded the horizons of research in ecology to new scales and ways
of thinking. In particular, studies of atmosphere-ecosystem interactions require
an understanding of ecological processes at spatial scales that have an impact on
the atmosphere. Interdisciplinary analyses of atmosphere-ecosystem interactions
and collaborations with atmospheric scientists now comprise a substantial portion
of NREL's effort in research and education and are likely to increase in the
future.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="../NREL/nrel_info.html">Back to the Index</A><P>
