<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  The Human Role in Ecosystem Dynamics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<A NAME="human"><H2>The Human Role in Ecosystem Dynamics</H2></A>
The role of humans in the structure and functioning of ecosystems is among the
principal topics of study at the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL), one
of the first research institutions to incorporate human ecology into the analysis
of ecosystems. This research tradition began in 1980 with the South Turkana
Ecosystem Project (STEP), an interdisciplinary study of the ecological role of
nomadic pastoralists in southern Kenya. Supported by the National Science
Foundation, STEP integrated the work of several social and environmental
scientists from Kenya and the United States.<P>
Over the 15 years since STEP began, NREL ecologists and anthropologists have
  developed three interrelated research themes that explore interactions between
  humans and their environment:<P>
<P>
<UL>
  <LI>the ecology of pastoralism
  <LI>climate change and human land use
  <LI>land use and biodiversity
</UL>
<P>
<B>Ecology of Pastoralism<P>
</B>Under the leadership of NREL ecologists Jim Ellis and David Swift and
anthropologists from the State University of New York at Binghamton, the South
Turkana project evolved a research approach that treated humans as interactive
components of the ecosystem, not simply as external driving forces or sources of
perturbation. STEP brought together ecological and anthropological perspectives
to examine the behavioral and biological adaptations f Turkana pastoralists to
ecosystem dynamics.<P>

<IMG SRC="donkey.gif"><BR>
<I>A village in central Niger, West Africa, during the dry season. Agriculture is
regularly practiced in this region, which only receives an average of 500-600
millimeters of rain a year. Photo by K.A. Galvin
</I><P>

Turkana strategies for coping with a harsh and highly seasonal environment include
  owning several species of livestock, such as camels, cattle, sheep, goats and
  donkeys; moving livestock daily in search of forage and water; migration out of
  the Turkana region during drought conditions; sharing food, and making sure that
  nutritional shortages are borne primarily by adults and older adolescents rather
  than young children. These strategies determine the flow of energy through the
  ecosystem to humans (Figure 1).<P>
Ellis, Swift and NREL anthropologist Kathleen Galvin conducted a study of the ways
  in which pastoralists cope with drought. NREL ecologist Michael Coughenour
  devised schemes to link remote sensing, geographic information systems (GIS) and
  spatial ecosystem models in a drought-monitoring or early-warning system for
  famine. His Savanna model includes a pastoralism component that simulates human
  energy intake, herd management and strategies for coping with droughts.<P>
NREL scientists are now comparing land-use patterns among pastoralists and
  agropastoralists in the Republic of China, in Mongolia and throughout Africa in
  order to see how populations respond to different ecological regimes. For
 example, Galvin's comparative nutritional studies have led to an analysis of the
impact of seasonal rainfall patterns on the viability of agriculture versus
pastoralism in east and west Africa.<P>
<P>
<B>Climate Change and Human Land Use<P>
</B>STEP was the first study to identify the pervasive role of climate variation
in dry ecosystems dominated by human populations. This theme encompasses two
principal topics: non-equilibrium dynamics and global environmental change.<P>
In the late 1980s, a synthesis by Ellis and Swift of data from STEP and other
  studies in Africa and Australia showed that dry tropical ecosystems are often
  dominated and controlled by climate variability rather than by biological
  interactions. This discovery has crucial implications for land use, ecosystem
  management, economic development, conservation of biodiversity and climate
  change over the 65% of the earth that is arid or semiarid.<P>
NREL scientists are currently conducting investigations in Africa and Mongolia to
  explore further the role of climate variability in human ecology and land use
  and to begin to determine the role of ecosystem instability in biodiversity and
  in the generation and loss of genetic variation in dryland organisms. We have
  also participated in syntheses sponsored by the U.S. National Academy of
  Sciences, the British Overseas Development Agency and the Norwegian Aid Agency
  that are aimed at elucidating the impact of climate variation on pastoral land
  use and livestock development. NREL research on land use in the U.S. shows that
  dryland agricultural practices in the central grasslands are also susceptible
  to changes in climate. Simulation studies using the Century model show, however,
  that changes in land use can override the effects of climate change in these
  temperate regions.<P>
Indeed, environmental factors alone do not determine land-use patterns or changes;
  human activities stimulate environmental change and often override natural
  ecosystem dynamics. NREL scientists are endeavoring to understand the impact of
  human land use and to determine how it contributes to environmental change.
  Several studies have begun to investigate the socioeconomic and environmental
  constraints on land-use decisions. Among them are studies of grazing patterns
  in the Mongolian steppe, of Conservation Reserve Programs in Colorado and of
  lad-use decisions for conservation reserves in Tanzania. Working with social
  scientists at University of Colorado, Galvin has found that conservation
  policies in the Ngorongoro Conservation Area of Tanzania have severely
  restricted pastoral land use. The economic viability of livestock production has
  decreased, and the lack of alternatives has compromised the economic state,
  health and nutritional status of pastoralists in the area, regardless of
  socioeconomic class (Figure 2).<P>
<P>
<B>Land Use and Biodiversity<P>
</B>Patterns of land use have major implications for the future of global
biological diversity as well as for human well-being. NREL scientists have studied
the relationship between biodiversity, conservation and human development in other
 countries and have focused on the interactions of biodiversity, conservation and
ecosystem management in the U.S.<P>
In conjunction with state and federal agencies, Coughenour, Thomas Stohlgren and
  Thompson Hobbs of the NREL are developing and testing field methods and GIS
  techniques at a scale useful to land managers. One study focuses on management
  issues in and adjacent to Rocky Mountain National Park in Colorado. Researchers
  are addressing strategic concerns for ecosystem management, including
  development, urbanization, invasive species and fragmented habitats. Another
  project includes developing a system for making land-use planning decisions in
 several counties in Colorado. Its purpose is to help planners assess the
potential impact of recreational facilities on wildlife diversity. The system
relies on a collaborative team of stakeholders from each county and on citizen
participation for testing and validation.<P>
Swift and University of Colorado scientists are collaborating with representatives
  of the Lakota (Sioux) Nation and the National Park Service to develop a wildlife
  management plan for southern parts of Badlands National Park that are also part
  of the Pine Ridge Reservation. The goal is to develop policies and procedures
  that are both founded on sound ecological principles and consistent with the
  Lakota view of humankind's relationship to the natural world.<P>
The conflicting needs of traditional societies and the conservation of biological
  resources are at the heart of a study, conducted by Galvin and Ellis, of the
  compatibility of human populations, livestock and wildlife in Tanzania. The NREL
  researchers are comparing the 'park&#34; model of biological conservation with
  a 'regional' or 'community' model that includes local human populations as
  stakeholders in wildlife conservation. The coexistence of Maasai pastoralists
  and wildlife in northern Tanzania is threatened as a result of the perceived
  conflict between conservation policy and the needs of the local people.
  Resolution of this issue is crucial in Africa as countries try to improve living
  standards through economic development while also preserving their wildlife
  resources, which provide considerable revenue from tourism.<P>
NREL studies also explore the dynamics of ecosystems dominated by humans in order
  to ensure that land-use planning and economic development preserve a balance
  between ecological sustainability and economic viability. Sustainable
  development is the ultimate goal of two projects in which NREL is participating.
  Ellis is working with former NREL student Robin Reid, now at the International
  Laboratory for Research on Animal Diseases in Nairobi, to assess the impact of
  efforts to control trypanosomiasis, the most serious disease of livestock in
  Africa, on agricultural production, human welfare and biodiversity. Swift is
  involved in a sustainableagriculture program of the U.S. Agency for
  International Development that includes local participation in the development
  process.<P>

<IMG SRC="kathy.gif"><BR>
<I>NREL anthropologist Kathleen Galvin takes anthropometric measurements to assessnutritional status of Maasai children in the Ngorongoro Conservation Area of
Tanzania.
</I><P>

Starting with the pioneering South Turkana project, NREL scientists have continued
  to explore the interaction of humans and the environment in a variety of ways.
  Research projects today address different geographic regions and different
  spatial scales. Studies have become more sophisticated with the use of GIS,
  satellite data, simulation models and theoretical models that include the
  socioeconomic and political factors affecting human behavior. The NREL continues
  its commitment to research on fundamental human ecological issues, including the
  impact of human populations on ecological systems and environmental influences
  on human behavior and biology.<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="../NREL/nrel_info.html">Back to the Index</A><P>
<A HREF="plant-animal.html">Next Section</A><P>

<P>
