</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Plant-Animal Interactions</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<A NAME="plant-animal"><H2>Studying the Role of Plant-Animal Interactions in Ecosystems Dynamics</H2></A>
Herbivory, the consumption of plants by animals, has a pervasive influence on
 the structure and functioning of ecosystems. It modifies the amount of energy
that moves through ecosystems, changes the pathways that energy follows and
affects the composition and nutrient cycling of plant communities. Studies
conducted in many parts of the world have demonstrated the importance of herbivory
in both natural ecosystems and those dominated by livestock. In grassland and
savanna ecosystems, herbivores above and below the soil surface consume between
10% and 90% of the net primary production. Energy and materials are thus diverted
from detrital food webs into herbivorous ones, many of which provide nutrition for
humans. Belowground herbivores, particularly nematodes, reduce plant production
by a quantity far greater than the biomass they consume.<P>
The Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL) has a long history of studying
  plant-animal interactions at all levels of biological organization, from
  organisms to ecosystems. Looking at these interactions from an interdisciplinary
  perspective, we examine the ways that herbivory influences the flows of carbon,
  nutrients and water throughout the ecosystem, and in turn, how changes in these
  fluxes affect other ecosystem components and dynamics. Our approach requires
  integrated studies of plants, soils, animals and, in certain contexts, human
  populations.<P>

<IMG SRC="bison.gif"><BR>
<I>Bison grazing in Yellowstone National Park. Photo by M.B. Coughenou</I><P>

Research at NREL on plant-animal interactions began with the International
  Biological Program's Grassland Biome Study (1967-1974), which involved extensive
  studies of vertebrate and invertebrate herbivory, both above and below ground,
  in the grasslands of the western United States. NREL scientists Daniel
  Milchunas, Debra Coffin, William Lauenroth and Ingrid Burke continue research
  on herbivory at sites in the Central Plains Experimental Range (CPER), now part
  of the Long-Term Ecological Research (LTER) program. Their findings show that
  different conclusions may be reached about the effects of livestock grazing,
  depending upon whether these effects are viewed from the perspective of plant
  community composition, primary production, nutrient cycling or other consumer
  populations. This diversity of views emphasizes the necessity of approaching
  questions about the role of herbivory from different levels of biological
  organization.<P>
<P>
<B>Plant-Animal Interactions at the Organism Level<P>
</B>NREL scientists have devoted considerable effort to studying organism-level
interactions between herbivores and plants. David Swift constructed a detailed
model of the effects of changes in quality of diet and availability of forage on
herbivore energy and nitrogen balance. Starting from this point, Swift and
Thompson Hobbs have developed increasingly sophisticated approaches to determining
how many herbivores a given ecosystem can support. Ongoing studies by Hobbs and
John Gross take a functional approach to understanding how plant density,
structure and tissue quality affect the rates at which individual animals consume
plants and how foraging behaviors are linked to animal body size. These studies
seek to develop general models that are widely applicable.<P>
Our studies at NREL have demonstrated a wide variety of plant responses to grazing
  and browsing, developed in response to long-term selective pressures. We have
  explained these responses in terms of numerous interacting processes and traits
  at the individual plant and leaf levels. James Detling and Michael Coughenour
  have found that increases in photosynthetic rates and shifts in carbon and
  nitrogen allocation contribute to the ability of plants to tolerate herbivory.
  Increases in nitrogen uptake rates have been documented in North American and
  African grasses and dwarf shrubs in response to herbivory. Genotypes of grasses
  adapted to grazing have been found on and near prairie-dog colonies in Wind Cave
  National Park, South Dakota. The allocation of energy and materials to root
  biomass partly explains the ability of North American shortgrass prairie species
  to resist grazing. Jim Ellis has shown that livestock in Kenya facilitate the
  regeneration of Acacia trees by eating and redistributing seedpods, a likely
  carryover of coevolution between Acacia and native ungulate species.<P>
<P>

<IMG SRC="tomh.gif"><BR>
<I>NREL researchers have pioneered the use of controlled experimental approaches to
the study of plant-animal interactions. Here Tom Hobbs is observing dietary
choices of tame big horn sheep in studies of the effects of fire on mountain shrub
ecosystems. Photo by John Gross </I><P>

<B>Population, Community and Ecosystem<P>
</B>The effects of these responses at the level of individual organisms are felt
at population, community and ecosystem levels as well. Gross and Francis Singer
are studying insular populations of native and exotic ungulates in U.S. western
national parks. Studies of bighorn sheep are carried out in 11 of these parks,
 where researchers are employing empirical and modeling studies of metapopulation
persistence, dispersal and gene flow to conserve populations and their genetic
diversities. Studies conducted by Detling and Coughenour in the Pryor Mountains
of Montana will be used to determine the size of wild (Spanish) horse populations
that can optimize the genetic diversity of the species while minimizing danger to
plant and soil resources.<P>
Community-level studies undertaken by Detling and his students in Wind Cave
  National Park have investigated the affinity of bison for areas around
  prairie-dog colonies. They demonstrated that prairie dog grazing maintains
  grasses in a state that provides higher levels of nutrition for bison. Hobbs and
  Swift have shown that grazing in herds may likewise facilitate an increased flow
  of nutrients to the animals in question. <P>
NREL scientists have also conducted numerous ecosystem-level studies. Detling's
  Wind Cave study went beyond the concerns of community ecology to study the role
  of herbivores in modifying primary production and nutrient cycling. Ellis,
  Swift, Coughenour and Kathleen Galvin have studied a nomadic pastoral ecosystem
  in northwest Kenya. Couhenour, Singer, Edward Elliott, Jeffrey Welker and David
  Valentine are currently conducting studies of herbivory in five western national
  parks. They are investigating the impact of interactions among ungulates, plants
  and soils on nutrient cycling, primary production and the relationship between
  plants and water. They are also examining interactions among elk, fire, riparian
  plants, beaver and hydrological features of the landscape.<P>
<P>
<B>From Ecosystems to Landscapes<P>
</B>Researchers at NREL are increasingly attempting to extend the scale of their
studies from the ecosystem to the landscape to improve their understanding of the
role of herbivores at larger spatial scales. Along with plant and soil processes,
herbivory is not uniform in its spatial distribution. We have found that spatial
heterogeneity must be considered if we are to succeed in using our observations
from leaves, plants and patches to provide integrated assessments of pasture,
landscape and regional systems.<P>
Several research programs are contributing to our understanding of the large-scale
  impact of herbivory. Detling's studies in Wind Cave National Park have
  documented large differences induced by herbivory in primary production and
  nutrient cycling within and outside prairie-dog colonies. Milchunas has found
  that grazing in the CPER decreases the heterogeneity of plant communities and
  soil nutrients at scales ranging from square meters to landscapes. Coughenour
  has carried out spatial modeling and empirical studies that have shown how the
  timing, intensity and duration of herbivory are affected by changes in elk
  distribution in response to snow, forage, cover and topography in Yellowstone
  and Rocky Mountain national parks and by patchy rainfall, forage and
  availability of water in pastoral ecosystems in Africa.<P>
Coughenour, Hobbs and Gross are using spatial ecosystem modeling, population
  modeling, geographic information systems and risk analysis in studies of
  ungulates in a wide variety of habitats (Figure 1). The foraging of large
  herbivores is influenced by factors that can be analyzed at a variety of scales,
  from plants and patches to landscapes and regions. <P>
Recent projects have begun to examine the links between biodiversity and ecosystem
  function. Coughenour, Thomas Stohlgren, and Daniel Binkley are conducting a
  landscape-scale 'gap analysis&#34; study to determine how measures of plant
  diversity at various levels of spatial resolution and sampling intensity are
  related to elk distributions and herbivory and historical changes in land use
  along the Colorado Front Range. This study aims to develop a general approach
  to assessing biodiversity at scales useful for management and planning.
  Conservation biology is central to Hobbs's study of spatial patterns and effects
  of fragmentation of wildlife habitats in areas of Colorado dominated by human
  activity.<P>
Belowground grazing is another area of interest to NREL researchers. William Hunt,
  Diana Freckman and Elliott have investigated underground foodwebs in Colorado
  grasslands and their response to climate change. Hunt has shown that
  invertebrate herbivory belowground supports complex food webs that may
  contribute to enhanced nutrient cycling. Freckman is studying the impact of
  disturbance on the diversity of soil nematodes in natural and agricultural
  ecosystems.<P>
NREL research on plant-animal interactions contributes to a deeper understanding
  of the structure and dynamics of natural and managed ecosystems. Ecosystem
  management is ultimately based upon theories of ecosystem function. One set of
  theories has emphasized the tendency f plants and herbivores to come into a
  dynamic equilibrium with one another at an ecological carrying capacity. Our
  research has shown that non-equilibrial tendencies must also be considered in
  the management of ungulates in U.S. national parks and in the economic
  development of pastoral ecosystems in developing countries. Similarly, the
  failure to consider the spatial aspects of plant-animal interactions can lead
  to inappropriate and unsustainable ecosystem 'design.&#34; Building upon a
  foundation of small-scale process studies and extrapolating the results to
  large-scale analyses, NREL research aims to provide a sound scientific basis for
  ecosystem management.<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="../NREL/nrel_info.html">Back to the Index</A><P>
