<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Ecosystem Modeling</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<A NAME="modeling"><H2>Ecosystem Modeling: Contributions to Synthesis</H2></A>
Scientists at the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL) have a long
tradition of developing and using mathematical models as a means of advancing
synthesis in ecology. Synthesis is the process of bringing together disparate
information into a unified whole in order to discover new patterns, mechanisms or
interactions. Its goal is to achieve a new level of understanding of complex
systems and thus to improve our ability to predict the ways in which such systems
will respond to change. Used in conjunction with results from field and laboratory
studies, modeling is a powerful tool for bringing together existing information
on the various components of ecosystems, finding the gaps in our knowledge and
advancing our understanding of how ecosystems work. A contemporary form of
synthesis that depends upon modeling is the projection of ecosystem responses to
scenarios of future conditions. Such projections are currently our only means of
predicting the impact on ecosystems of large-scale, long-term changes in climate
and other critical variables.
Modeling efforts at NREL are primarily directed towards understanding how the
  major components of ecosystems, such as plants, animals, soils, nutrients and
  water, interact with each other and with external factors such as atmospheric
  conditions. Although NREL modelers have traditionally focused their efforts on
  grassland, savanna and agricultural ecosystems, current studies also include
  work on tundra ecosystems, shrublands and forests. Modeling studies are used to
  provide practical assessments of the impact of resource management practices and
  potential changes in climate as well as to advance our scientific knowledge.<P>

<IMG SRC="tam_moh.gif"><BR>
<I>Tammy Bearly, left, and Mohammed Kalkhan. Photo by William Cotton</I><P>

Ecosystem modeling at NREL has its roots in the research that began with the
  Grassland Biome Study in the late 1960s, one of the first large-scale ecosystem
  modeling efforts to be attempted. One of the early goals was to develop a
  general grassland model, a synthesis that would simulate ecosystem dynamics for
  diverse grassland types, include all of the major ecosystem components and be
  able to respond to changes in management practices and atmospheric
  conditions.<p>
Following this early tradition, most of the models developed at NREL are created
  in the context of large, interdisciplinary projects that include field and
  laboratory experiments as well as modeling. Models are used to guide the
  formulation of experiments, the results of which are used, in turn, to test and
  revise the models. This interaction between model development and field research
  yields new insights into the structure and functioning of whole ecosystems and
  their potential response to change.<P>
NREL scientists have focused from the beginning on the cycling of carbon, nitroge
  and phosphorus through and within ecosystems. More recent research has advanced
  modeling representations of interactions among element cycles and of key
  processes such as primary production, nutrient mineralization, and soil organic
  matter (SOM) formation and loss. Much of this work has been devoted to poorly
  understood belowground processes such as root production and exudation,
  mycorrhizal activity and microbial production as well as SOM formation. Modeling
  studies conducted by William Lauenroth, William Hunt and others have shown that
  standard estimates of root production may seriously underestimate actual
  production.<P>
Field and laboratory research on soil fauna and nutrient mineralization led to
  modeling studies by Hunt and John Moore that focused on the relationships
  between complexity, diversity, stability, productivity and the flow of energy
  among species in detrital food webs (Figure 1). Studies such as these bring
  together the traditional methods and interests of biogeochemistry and community
  ecology.<P>
<P>
<B>Impact Assessment<P>
</B>Models developed at NREL have been used to assess the impact of potential
changes in climate, atmospheric gas concentrations and grazing patterns on
grasslands in the United States and elsewhere. Since the 1970s, NREL scientists
have used grassland ecosystem models to evaluate the impact of climate change
scenarios on plant and animal production, nutrient cycling and sustainability of
grasslands. These efforts were stimulated initially by questions about the impact
of cloud seeding and supersonic transport on climate and more recently by concerns
about the effects on ecosystems of the increased temperatures and altered
precipitation patterns that could result from an increase in atmospheric
greenhouse gases such as methane (CH<em sub>4</em>), nitrous oxide (N<em sub>2</em>O) and
carbon dioxide (CO2).
Hunt, David Schimel, William Parton and Dennis Ojima have conducted a number of
  modeling studies aimed at evaluating both the potential direct effects of
  increased levels of atmospheric CO<em sub>2</em> on grasslands and the combined
  impact of both increased CO2 and changes in climate. Results from this work
  showed that increases in atmospheric CO2 can bring about increases in plant
  production but that the long-term rate of increase is moderated by the
  availability of nitrogen in the soil. An accompanying decrease in the nitrogen
  content of plant material, however, is likely to decrease animal production.
  Although the impact of changes in both atmospheric CO2 levels and climate is
  much less certain, our models are being used to design experiments that will
  improve our understanding of their combined effects.
Our efforts at modeling agricultural ecosystems (agroecosystems) address the
  question of how environmental factors and management practices interact in
  controlling production and nutrient dynamics in agricultural systems. Studies
  span a range of temporal and spatial scales, from a detailed examination of
  management effects on ecosystem carbon and nutrient fluxes at a single field
  site to long-term, regional assessments of productivity and soil organic matter
  in relation to major land-use and climate change patterns. Although most of
  these studies use the Century model, developed by Parton, Vernon Cole and
 others, to analyze temperate-zone agricultural systems in North America, we are
also undertaking studies of agricultural systems elsewhere in the world.<P>
NREL researchers have also developed models for assessing the impact of
  contaminants on humans and ecosystems. In one study, Thomas Kirchner and
  colleagues from the Department of Radiolgical Health Sciences at Colorado State
  University computed doses received by people in communities surrounding the
  Nevada nuclear bomb test site. The effort required simulating the transport of
  radionuclides through agroecosystems. Although external exposures tended to
  dominate total body doses, the ingestion of contaminated milk was responsible
  for significant thyroid doses. The model also demonstrated the importance of
  taking into account agricultural practices and the transport of contaminated
  milk within a region. People in communities that received no fallout were
  affected nevertheless because they drank contaminated milk imported from other
  areas. The model resulting from this effort was also used to help evaluate the
  impact on human populations of fallout from the 1986 Chernobyl reactor accident
  in the Ukraine.<P>
Our experience with contaminant transport modeling is now being applied to the
  development of models for assessing risks to ecological systems as well as to
  humans (Figure 2). In collaboration with researchers from Colorado State
  University's Center for Ecological Risk Assessment and Management, Kirchner is
  working on ways to improve the quality and facilitate the construction of models
  for evaluating the effects of contaminants on ecosystems.<P>
<P>
<B>Integrated Modeling<P>
</B>Researchers at the NREL have developed integrated modeling programs that focus
on the interactions of different components in ecosystems. Among these are models
that look at the interaction of herbivores and plants and the short- and long-term
impact of grazing management practices in grassland ecosystems. These models have
been extended to evaluate the effect of management practices on the economic
viability of grazing systems and the consequences for the human populations that
rely on them.<P>
Michael Coughenour, David Swift, Jim Ellis and Kathleen Galvin have combined
  modeling with field research in their studies of a pastoral ecosystem in
  Turkana, Kenya. The South Turkana Ecosystem Project (STEP) synthesized data on
  plant distribution and production, animal production and human nutrition.
  Analyzing these data within a geographic information system (GIS), the team
  developed a static model of annual energy flow through the ecosystem. This
  analysis clearly revealed the importance of browse and browsers (camels) in what
  was thought to be a grazing ecosystem and a socioeconomic system dominated by
  cattle.<P>
Early STEP simulation modeling efforts focused on plant and animal production and
  dynamics. Later models of the pastoral enterprise included such variables as
  livestock management, tactics for coping with drought and human nutrition. Among
  these was Savanna, a spatially organized dynamic ecosystem model, developed in
  order to assess the significance of landscape heterogeneity and the migration
  patterns of the nomadic herdsmen. Monthly vegetation indices and other GIS data
  were used for inputs and verification. The model demonstrated the importance of
  pastoral mobility as a strategy for dealing with temporal changes in forage
  availability. It also showed how water redistribution in the landscape affects
  vegetation and ecosystem dynamics, resulting in relatively productive patches
  within an arid system.<P>
One of the first spatially explicit ecosystem models, Savanna is also being used
  by Coughenour, Swift, Galvin and Ellis for analysis of several North American
  ecosystems dominated by large herbivores (Figure 3).<p>

<A HREF="mikec.gif"><IMG SRC="../ABOUTNREL/mikec.gif"></A><P>
<I>Figure 3: Overall structure of Savanna, a spatially explicit, dynamic ecosystem
model that was originally developed for studies of African pastoralism. It has
also been applied to western U.S. and Canadian national parks as an ecosystem
management model. Ungulates and their interactions with plants are a principal
concern. Savanna is unique in representing linkages between plant production and
population processes as well as between ungulate energy balance and their
population processes. Primary production is tied directly to the soil water
budget. The model uses geographic information systems for both data input and
output.
</I><P>

In another synthesis project, Lauenroth and Debra Coffin integrated Steppe, a
  model that simulates the recruitment, growth and mortality of individual plants,
  with Solwat, a multilayer soil process model. Steppe was recently modified to
  simulate the ways in which grass types might shift in the mixed-grass and
  tallgrass prairies of the central Great Plains by incorporating competition for
  nitrogen and light in addition to competition for water.<P>
The linked Steppe-Soilwat model was used to assess the effects of changes in
  climate on the composition and structure of grassland vegetation. Preliminary
  simulations suggest that although different types of vegetation respond
  differently to climate change, shifts in types occur within 40 years of the
  change in conditions. Warm-season (C<em sub>4</em>) grasses increase in dominance
  or importance with a change in climate, primarily as a result of increases in
  temperature. These predicted shifts in the dominance and importance of
  cool-season (C<em sub>3</em>) versus warm-season grasses have important
  implications for the management of natural grasslands as well as the cultivation
  of crops in the central grassland region.
<HR>
<P>
