<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NREL Brochure:  Educational Activities</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<A NAME="education"><H2>Educational Activities</H2></A>
Although the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL) is a center for
research rather than an academic department, it participates actively in the
educational mission of Colorado State University. Its staff members teach courses
in various university departments, supervise graduate and postgraduate research
and share their knowledge with students at local schools and community
organizations.
The laboratory provides research opportunities, supervision and support for
  graduate students and postdoctoral fellows who participate in its programs. Over
  the last five years, NREL has supported 26 graduate students and 14 postdoctoral
  fellows with funds derived from research grants. During their years at the
  laboratory, these students have the opportunity to work closely with active
  researchers, both staff members and visitors. They have access to excellent
  computing and analytical facilities and technical support, attend and make
  presentations at national meetings, and participate in the process of writing
  grant proposals and papers for publication.<P>
NREL scientists also advise graduate students who receive support from sources
  other than NREL research projects. Scientists often undertake responsibility for
  the graduate education of students who arrive with their own funding but no
  adviser, just as departmental faculty members do. Among the organizations that
  have supported students at NREL in recent years are the U.S. Agency for
  International Development, the African Development Bank, the U.S. Department of
  Interior's National Park Service and National Biological Survey, Rotary
  International, and various national governments. Some 60 graduate students, in
  addition to those mentioned above, have benefited from the guidance of NREL
  staff members over the last five years.<P>
Nine NREL scientists have joint appointments and teach courses in the College of
  Natural Resources and other colleges at the university. During 1993, laboratory
  staff members taught 10 graduate-level courses with a total enrollment of 180
  students. Many serve as members of graduate student committees; the total over
  the last five years is more than 150.<P>
NREL plays a significant part in undergraduate education as well. During 1993,
  staff members taught eight undergraduate courses with a total enrollment of more
  than 1,000. The laboratory has provided 20 undergraduate students with research
  opportunities over the last five years through the "Research Experiences for
  Undergraduates&#34; program of the National Science Foundation (NSF). Research
  projects also provide financial support and experience for many other
 undergraduate students who are hired as hourly employees to work on laboratory
analyses or to collect field data for research projects. During the last five
years, 195 undergraduates have worked at NREL.<P>
Like their academic colleagues, NREL scientists contribute to education at the
  university in many other ways. Some serve on departmental, college and
  university committees dealing with such matters as curriculum, scholastic
  standards and admission. Others serve as mentors to minority undergraduates.
  Staff members often give guest lectures in courses taught on campus. These
  lectures provide an opportunity to discuss current research with students,
  enriching the educational experience and demonstrating the role of research in
  the generation of new knowledge.<P>
NREL staff members are frequently invited to make presentations on such topics as
  acid deposition, atmospheric pollution or wildlife conservation for students at
  local schools and colleges. They also speak regularly at meetings of
  conservation groups and other public organizations. One scientist has served as
  a mentor for Native American high school students who are interested in science.
  Another has instructed junior high school students on using the Internet. Yet
  another has taught an adult education course on arctic ecology.<P>
High school students have participated in NREL research projects from time to
  time. With support from the NSF, one high school senior from Nevada worked at
  the NREL for two weeks during the summer of 1994 and traveled to Antarctica the
  following January to participate in a field project in the Dry Valleys near
  McMurdo Station.<P>
<IMG SRC="ted.gif"><BR>
<I>NREL scientist Edward Elliott shows sixth graders Allison Anne Hurt, Jessica
Olguin, and Aaron Beach how to determine soil texture. Photo by Jafe Parsons</I>
<P>
<HR>
