<TITLE>Human Dimensions</TITLE>
<center><H1>Human Dimensions</H1></center>
<HR>
<P>
The role of humans in the structure and functioning of ecosystems is among the
principal topics of study at the Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory (NREL), one
of the first research institutions to incorporate human ecology into the analysis
of ecosystems. This research tradition began in 1980 with the South Turkana
Ecosystem Project (STEP), an interdisciplinary study of the ecological role of
nomadic pastoralists in southern Kenya. Supported by the National Science
Foundation, STEP integrated the work of several social and environmental
scientists from Kenya and the United States.
Click <A HREF="../../ABOUTNREL/human.html">here</A> for a more detailed description of
the human role in ecosystem dynamics research at NREL.
<P>
<H2>Human Dimensions Projects at NREL:</H2>
<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="../AGRICULTURE/ADAPT.html">ADAPT-II</A> - Spatially Explicit Projections of C Dynamics with Global Change in the Central U.S.
  <LI><A HREF="GED.html">Analysis of Past and Current Changes in Grassland Ecosystem Dynamics in Asia and North America</A>
  <LI><A HREF="../AGRICULTURE/CLUC.html">CLUC</A> - A Hierarchical Approach to Integrated Assessment of Climate and Land Use Changes with an Application to the Central US
  <LI><A HREF="WATERSH.html">Cross-site Watershed Analysis of Stream Riparian Dynamics</A>
  <LI><A HREF="CRSP.html">CRSP</A> - Modeling support to the SANREM CRSP
  <LI><A HREF="../AGRICULTURE/NIH.html">NIH</A> - Population and Environment in the US Great Plains
  <LI><A HREF="PLANTDIV.html">Landscape-scale Patterns of Plant Diversity</A>
  <LI><A HREF="../AGRICULTURE/LUCCI.html">LUCCI</A> - Land Use and Climate Change Impacts on Carbon Fluxes
  <LI><A HREF="MONG.html">MONG</A> - Integegrated Assessment of the Effects of Climate and Land Use Change on Ecosystem Dynamics, Stability and Resilience on the Mongolian Steppe
  <LI><A HREF="SCOP/scop.html">SCoP</A> -  A System for Conservation Planning
  <LI><A HREF="TANZ.html">TANZ</A> - Biological Conservation and Human Ecology: Conflict or Compatibility Between Wildlife and Pastoralists in Sub-Saharan Africa
</UL>
<HR>
