<TITLE>Plant-Animal Interactions</TITLE>
<center><H1>Plant-Animal Interactions</H1></center>
<HR>
<P>
Herbivory, the consumption of plants by animals, has a pervasive influence on
 the structure and functioning of ecosystems. It modifies the amount of energy
that moves through ecosystems, changes the pathways that energy follows and
affects the composition and nutrient cycling of plant communities. Studies
conducted in many parts of the world have demonstrated the importance of herbivory
in both natural ecosystems and those dominated by livestock. In grassland and
savanna ecosystems, herbivores above and below the soil surface consume between
10% and 90% of the net primary production. Energy and materials are thus diverted
from detrital food webs into herbivorous ones, many of which provide nutrition for
humans. Belowground herbivores, particularly nematodes, reduce plant production
by a quantity far greater than the biomass they consume.
Click <A HREF="../../ABOUTNREL/plant-animal.html">here</A> for a more detailed description of
plant-animal interaction studies at NREL.
<P>
<H2>Plant-Animal Interaction Projects at NREL:</H2>
<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="ATRIPLEX.html">Grazing Relations in <i>Atriplex canescens</i></A>  
