<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Ditylenchus/Alfalfa Research</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H2>Alfalfa stem nematode, Colorado State University</H2>
<H3>Within-plant Distribution, Varietal Response, and Early Season Management
of Alfalfa Foliar Nematodes in Colorado</H3>
<!<IMG SRC="" align=middle> <!<IMG SRC="" align=middle> <BR>
<BR>
We are investigating environmental modification and plant resistance as
ways to reduce alfalfa disease incited by Ditylenchus dipsaci in Colorado.
Three objectives, each with associated research questions, govern the investigation.
(1) Determine the within-plant distribution of D. dipsaci and Aphelenchoides
ritzemabosi. Are the two nematodes distributed differently within infected
plants? Does nematode distribution within plants change throughout the growing
season? Does nematode distribution within plants differ between resistant
and susceptible varieties? (2) Identify alfalfa varieties expressing resistance
to field populations of nematodes. Do varieties express differential resistance
to nematodes? Do patterns of resistance and susceptibility vary throughout
the growing season? How are population abundances related to yield? (3)
Modify the environment to reduce initial nematode populations. Does the
application of carbofuran reduce nematode populations and the incidence
of disease? Does plant response to carbofuran vary between resistant and
susceptible varieties? <BR>
<H3>Investigators:</H3>
<A HREF="/PEOPLE/niles.html">Robert Niles</A> &
<A HREF="/PEOPLE/freckman.html">Diana Freckman</A> <!<H3><!FUNDING:<!</H3>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="../SOILBIODIVERSITY.html"><IMG SRC="../images/acrobeles.gif" ALIGN=
"MIDDLE" ALT="[Soil Biodiversity Home]" WIDTH="60" HEIGHT="32" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0"></A> <A HREF="../SOILBIODIVERSITY.html">Return to the Soil Biodiversity
& Ecosystem Research Home Page </A><BR>
