<html>
<head>
<title>BOREAS</title>
</head>
<body>
<h3>Project Name:  Field micrometeorological measurements,
process-level studies, and modeling of methane and carbon dioxide
fluxes in a boreal wetland ecosystem (BOREAS project)</h3>
Funding Level: $50,000 per annum (CSU portion), 1993-1997<p>

Description:<p>

Based on our earlier laboratory work on methane production from northern wetland peats, we
had found that the quantity of substrate generated by fermentation processes--and the quality of
organic matter from which it derives--was a more important control over methanogenesis than
temperature.  Our participation in this BOREAS project presented an opportunity to examine the
importance of litter quantity and quality to methane emission rates in a field setting.  Our major
field season was summer, 1994, during which we applied a 2x2 factorial combination of carbon
(C, as wheat straw) and nitrogen (N, as urea) and tracked resulting changes in CH4 emissions. 
Our measured fluxes from control areas were highly consistent in magnitude and timing with
those derived from the eddy correlation technique, and CH4 emission and residue decomposition
rates were higher with added N than without.  In conjunction with our NIGEC-supported work in
the Sandhills wetlands, we are now incorporating these results into our process-level model of
CH4 emissions in wetlands.<p>

Funding Agency:  National Science Foundation<p>

Research Scientists and Collaborators:  <p>

	NREL PI: David Valentine<p>

	NREL Co-PI: Dave Schimel and Bill Parton<p>

	External Collaborators: <p>

		PI:  Shashi B. Verma, University of Nebraska<p>

		Co-PI:  T.J. Arkebauer and F.G. Ullman, University of Nebraska<p>

<HR>
